{"TopicId":113430,"ForumId":20,"TopicTitle":"gravity depending of height","CreatedByName":"Skalou","CreatedById":133496,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-06-19T18:56:55Z","PageNum":1,"Articles":[{"CreatedByName":"Skalou","CreatedById":133496,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-06-19T18:56:55Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003Ehello,\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E i would like to know what is the gravity(g) at differents altitudes, does the IRL formula works for KSP?\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cimg src=\u0022http://i.imgur.com/1tZIHFN.png\u0022 alt=\u00221tZIHFN.png\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDo you have a number for G(the big one)? or at least some g (the small) references, for exemple g/Kerbin-asl=1 (=9.81m/\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2) ,g/Kerbin-100km=?\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethank you\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEdit:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EArgh sorry i am in the wrong section, i wanted to post it in the \u0022General KSP Discussion\u0022\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eso is there a modded part displaying it? \u003Cimg src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_cheesy.gif\u0022 alt=\u0022:D\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222015-06-19T19:01:51Z\u0022 title=\u002206/19/2015 07:01  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00229 yr\u0022\u003EJune 19, 2015\u003C/time\u003E by Skalou\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"monstah","CreatedById":95210,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-06-19T20:18:20Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003Eg @ Kerbin ASL = 9.81m/s\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2 as in Earth, radius is 600km (or is that the diameter? damn). So G*kerbin mass= 9.81*600\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2 (or 300\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2...), from there you can calculate at any height\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022font-size:8px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022color:#C0C0C0;\u0022\u003E- - - Updated - - -\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlso, the Gravioli Detector is a stock part that measures it \u003Cimg src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_wink.gif\u0022 alt=\u0022;)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Skalou","CreatedById":133496,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-06-19T21:51:31Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022monstah\u0022 data-cite=\u0022monstah\u0022\u003E\u003Cdiv\u003Eg @ Kerbin ASL = 9.81m/s\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2 as in Earth, radius is 600km (or is that the diameter? damn). So G*kerbin mass= 9.81*600\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2 (or 300\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2...), from there you can calculate at any height\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022font-size:8px;\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022color:#C0C0C0;\u0022\u003E- - - Updated - - -\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlso, the Gravioli Detector is a stock part that measures it \u003Cimg src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_wink.gif\u0022 alt=\u0022;)\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003C/blockquote\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWoow, i\u0027m so ashamed now to didn\u0027t remember this \u003Cimg src=\u0022//kerbal-forum-uploads.s3.us-west-2.amazonaws.com/emoticons/default_k_cheesy.gif\u0022 alt=\u0022:D\u0022\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eand you are right, i can do my own science,\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eso, that\u0027s what i\u0027ve done:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E-experiment in KSP with the Gravioli Detector on Kerbin: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eon the launchpad; g0=9.81m/s\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eg in orbit at the altitude of 100 000m; g100 000=7.21m/s\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2 \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Eg in orbit at the altitude of 1 000 000m; g1 000 000=1.38m/s\u00C3\u201A\u00C2\u00B2\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Efrom the wiki: \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E[TABLE]\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E[TR]\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E[TD=colspan: 2] Mkerbin=[/TD]\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E[TD] 5.2915793\u00C3\u0192\u00E2\u20AC\u201D10\u003Csup\u003E22\u003C/sup\u003E kg[/TD]\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E[/TR]\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E[/TABLE]\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Er=Kerbin radius \u002B altitude\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EKerbin radius= 600 000m\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003Ethe calculs are ok with G=6.674x10^-11 (maybe [m]^3/\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E^2/[kg] )\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003Ethe G is different of the \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_gravitational_parameter\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003EStandard gravitational parameter\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E from the wiki: 3.5316000\u00C3\u0192\u00E2\u20AC\u201D10\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E12\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E m\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E3\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E2\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003Ethank you for your answer, that\u0027s why i like forum , i could have scratched my head many times...\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003EEdit:\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003Ehey, i understand better why we are accelerating so slow at an high Ap of an elliptic orbit now.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n\u003Cspan class=\u0022ipsType_reset ipsType_medium ipsType_light\u0022 data-excludequote=\u0022\u0022\u003E\n\u003Cstrong\u003EEdited \u003Ctime datetime=\u00222015-06-19T22:09:53Z\u0022 title=\u002206/19/2015 10:09  PM\u0022 data-short=\u00229 yr\u0022\u003EJune 19, 2015\u003C/time\u003E by Skalou\u003C/strong\u003E\n\u003C/span\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"TheShadow1138","CreatedById":53694,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-06-21T06:19:09Z","Content":"\n\u003Cblockquote data-ipsquote=\u0022\u0022 class=\u0022ipsQuote\u0022 data-ipsquote-username=\u0022Skalou\u0022 data-cite=\u0022Skalou\u0022\u003E\u003Cdiv\u003EG=6.674x10^-11 (maybe [m]^3/\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E^2/[kg] )\u003C/span\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003Ethe G is different of the \u003C/span\u003E\u003Ca href=\u0022https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_gravitational_parameter\u0022 rel=\u0022external nofollow\u0022\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003EStandard gravitational parameter\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/a\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E from the wiki: 3.5316000\u00C3\u0192\u00E2\u20AC\u201D10\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E12\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E m\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E3\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E2\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/div\u003E\u003C/blockquote\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003EJust thought I\u0027d clarify a bit here. The G, sometimes called \u0022Big G\u0022 is the \u0022Universal Gravitational Constant\u0022, which is 6.67 x 10\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E-11\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E with units of m\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E3\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E/kg/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E2\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003EThe \u0022Standard Gravitational Parameter\u0022 is the product of a body\u0027s mass and the Universal Gravitational Constan (M*G). So this wiki\u0027s quoted value of 3.5316000 x 10\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E12\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E m\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E3\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E2\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E is the product of Kerbin\u0027s mass and Big G:\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E(5.2915793 x 10\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E22\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003Ekg * 6.67 x 10\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E-11\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003Em\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E3\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E/kg/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E2\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E) = 3.5316000 x 10\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E12\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E m\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E3\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E/s\u003C/span\u003E\u003Csup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E2\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/sup\u003E\u003Cspan style=\u0022text-decoration:line-through;\u0022\u003E.\u003C/span\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\n"},{"CreatedByName":"Requia","CreatedById":112924,"CreatedDateTime":"2015-06-21T20:34:28Z","Content":"\n\u003Cp\u003EThe mass and GM (this saves so much calculator button pushes) of all celestial bodies is listed if you click the buttons on the right in the tracking station, or focus on the body in map mode.\u003C/p\u003E\n"}]}